 reflect rising interest in the medieval Norse and their North American presence. Uniquely in reception studies, From Iceland to the Americas approaches this dynamic between Nordic history and its reception by bringing together international authorities on mythology, language, film and cultural studies, as well as on the literature that has dominated critical reception. Collectively, the chapters not only explore the connections among medieval Iceland and the modern Americas, but also probe why medieval contact has become a modern cultural touchstone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGeographical discoveries in literature. 0aOld Norse literaturexAppreciation. 0aVikings in literature. 4aLiterature Studies 2021. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Scandinavian.2bisacsh  a1893 Chicago World’s Fair.  aImmigration.  aLeif Eriksson.  aMythology.  aNorse gods.  aOld Norse sagas.  aPoetic Edda.  aPopular culture.  aReception studies.  aVinland.1 aGeeraert, Dustin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalink, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarty, Kevin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelgason, Jón Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelgason, Jón Karl, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHöfig, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLerer, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLethbridge, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMachan, Tim William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMachan, Tim William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt